1 Identifiers

Python is an â€œobject orientated programming languageâ€.

In Python everything is an â€œobjectâ€. Weâ€™ll look at some of the common ones in this section, like lists, tuples and dictionaries. Weâ€™ll also look at some specialised objects â€“ like series and data frames from the Pandas module.

1.1 Variables

When we create objects in Python we assign it to a variable.

Variables are words and numbers that act like labels; a reference to an object that lives in memory.

Without this variable we canâ€™t â€œfindâ€ the object again in memory and wonâ€™t be able to use it.

In Python we assign variables using the equals sign ( = )

Our label (or variable name) goes on the left of the equals sign.

The object we want to store goes on the right of the equals sign.

In Python we do not have to state the data type of variable we are storing.

x = 4 + 3

Here we are storing an object (the sum of 4 + 3) and giving it the label of x.

Youâ€™ll notice that when we run the cell above it does not output the value of x.

To see the value of x we can give Python the variable name, run the cell and it will output the value

x
## 7

Why do we have to ask Jupyter to output things?

When we assign a variable Python keeps it stored within memory for later use. While weâ€™re learning or testing our code we may want to check our outputs regularly.

However, once weâ€™re confident the code operates as expected outputting every stage isnâ€™t necessary â€“ in fact itâ€™s not an efficient use of memory.

x = 4 + 3
y = "Hello"
x
y

If the above code is run in Jupyter you will only see the output for the value of y.

Jupyter prints one output per cell by default. N.B - the software used to create this HTML outputs both values - so the output of the above cell has been supressed.

If I want to print more I can use the print() function.

print(x, y)
## 7 Hello

Some users will add in additional text strings here to explain results. For example:

print(y, "I am", x, "years old")
## Hello I am 7 years old

You will see a lot of the solutions in this course wrapped in print() functions â€“ to avoid using multiple cells.

Finally â€“ we can overwrite the values of a variable by reassigning it.

y had the value of "Hello"

This code below will now give it the value of 26.

We should be careful when weâ€™re assigning variables as Python does not warn us if a variable already exists!

y = 26
y
## 26

1.2 Naming Conventions

Naming your variables can be one of the trickier parts of coding.

Choosing sensible names saves time and energy later, when you try and remember what youâ€™ve called something.

Clever naming allows you to figure out what an object contains without having to inspect it.

A variable name:

  • Must start with a letter or an underscore
  • Canâ€™t begin with a number
  • Only contain alphanumeric characters and underscores
  • Is case sensitive (MY_VARIABLE and my_variable and My_vArIaBle are treated independently)
  • Must not have hyphens

You may also have your own departmental guidance for naming variables.

General guidance recommends Pythonâ€™s pep8 coding standards use of lowercase_with_underscores.

Consistency is important â€“ if you pick up your code after 6 months, or pass code on to your colleagues, using consistent names ensures your code works and improves the quality.

â€œAlways code as if the guy who ends up maintaining your code will be a violent psychopath who knows where you live. Code for readability.â€ - John F Woods

The Data Science Campus have their style guide linked online.

Through this course we will use lower case words with an underscore between them, e.g:

music_df  # The contents should be a DataFrame

cars_model # The contents should be a model

names_list # The contents should be a list

2.3 Strings

Strings are sequences of character data. The type in Python is called str.

Strings are contained within either â€˜singleâ€™ or â€œdoubleâ€ quotation marks.

All characters between the opening and the closing quote are part of the string.

As you can see by running the cell above strings can also contain numbers and punctuation. Weâ€™ll look at this again later when we import data.

The choice between single and double quotes is up to the user.

We reccomend that if youâ€™re creating strings that use apostrophes or single quote marks, use double quotes to open and close your string.

Notice how the whole strings are the same colour in the second example.

This is something known as syntax highlighting and can be very useful to ensure youâ€™ve closed your strings.

2.5 Boolean

Boolean values are sometimes called logical values in other languages.

There are two values True and False.

In Python they must be spelt out fully and have a capital first letter. They are not text values; so do not require quote marks. They are a reserved word, and so are displayed in bold green text.

As weâ€™ll see later Python often evaluates expressions in a Boolean context; something is either â€œtrueâ€ or â€œfalseâ€.

True has the value of 1 and False has the value of 0.

print(type(True), type(False))
## <class 'bool'> <class 'bool'>

In this section we are going to explore some of the common data structures in Python. Python is whatâ€™s known as an object orientated programming language. We create objects to do things to. Weâ€™ve already created objects (everything is an object in Python) but as we move into later sections of the course and in your own searches you may hear these data structures referred to as objects.

You may also hear the word â€œclassâ€ which is a template for how all instances of that object are created. Objects of the same class may look different but have key elements that are the same. A class of â€œbirdâ€ may have the instances â€œNorwegian Blue Parrotâ€, â€œBudgieâ€ and â€œEmuâ€ â€“ they all look very different but are all fundamentally birds.

A very large Norwegian Blue, Budgie and Emu

3.1 Lists

A list is a type of container; it holds a collection of items.

The items in a list have an order (an index)

Lists are mutable, we can change items in them and add or delete items,

We create lists using square brackets [ ] and separate each item with a comma.

Lists * Are the most versatile of the built-in data structures * Can hold any sequence of objects * Can hold mixed objects (like strings, integers and Booleans together) * Are mutable (can be changed)

Lists can also do more advanced things than we talk about in this course. You may come across those as you progress with your code.

# Create my list

the_pythons = ["Chapman", "Idle", "Gillam", "Jones", "Cleese", "Palin"]

# Display my list

the_pythons
## ['Chapman', 'Idle', 'Gillam', 'Jones', 'Cleese', 'Palin']

Here we have created a list with the variable name the_pythons.

We assign values to this using the = sign

These values are the strings "Chapman" , "Idle", "Gilliam", "Jones", "Cleese" and "Palin"

Because weâ€™re storing more than one value we need to use a list.

To create our list we pleace square brackets [ ] around the values.

Each value is separated by a comma.

We print out the contents of the list by giving Python the variable name - the_pythons.

Weâ€™ll often see lists and tuples as inputs or outputs for the programming we do.

We canâ€™t do that to tuples; the only thing we can do is write over them in memory by assigning a new tuple to the same variable.

Thatâ€™s not changing the values in the tuple; but overwriting it â€“ a technical but important difference.

3.5 Dictionaries

The third object type weâ€™ll look at is Dictionaries.

Dictionaries also store a collection of objects.

Whereas lists and tuples have an order (an index); Dictionaries are unordered.

Dictionaries are also * Mutable (can be altered) * Can contain lists and other (nested) dictionaries.

Dictionaries are created using curly braces { }

Dictionaries contain key value pairs.

Keys are usually integers or strings (an immutable data type)

** Values** can be any type of object

Keys and values are separated by a colon ( : )

# Create my dictionary

brian_information = {"name": "Brian Cohen",
                     "occupation": ["messiah ", "very naughty boy"],  # more than one value gets stored in a list
                     "enemy": "Pontius Pilate",
                     "outlook": "Look on the bright side of life"}

# Print the dictionary

brian_information
## {'name': 'Brian Cohen', 'occupation': ['messiah ', 'very naughty boy'], 'enemy': 'Pontius Pilate', 'outlook': 'Look on the bright side of life'}

In this example we have the keys name, occupation, enemy and outlook - which all have associated values.

Most have one associated value â€“ like Brian Cohen for the key name.

The key occupation has one associated value, a list. But this list contains multiple elements within itself. This allows us to be flexible with our values.

Depending on your version of Python the dictionary may print out in alphabetical order or the order you supplied the values in. Weâ€™ll see later on that we index (look up values) in a dictionary by the â€œkeyâ€; so it doesnâ€™t matter how it displays.

4 Indexing

We can select items from our lists, tuples and dictionaries. To do so we use square brackets [ ] .

Letâ€™s look at the list the_pythons we defined earlier

_example

We can select items from our lists, tuples and dictionaries. To do so we use square brackets [ ] .

Letâ€™s look at the list the_pythons we defined earlier

Each item within our list (or tuple) has an index. This relates to itâ€™s position in the list.

Python starts indexing at 0 â€“ which may be different to some other languages youâ€™ve used. (Think of it as starting on the ground floor of a building, then going up to the first floor).

In order to return the element in the list we can simply give the object name, then the index of the item we want to return within square brackets.

The code below will return the value Jones

the_pythons[3]
## 'Jones'

We can also use whatâ€™s known as negative indexing.

_example

The code in the next cell will return the same values. This can be useful if you want to return the last element; without knowing how many elements there are in your object.

print(the_pythons[0], the_pythons[-6])
## Chapman Chapman

For a list, we can use also use this indexing to overwrite values in a list. As tuples are immutable, and cannot be changed once created, this would not work on the days_of_the_week tuple.

the_pythons[4] = "Cheese" # Select the item at index 4 and overwrite it with "Cheese"

# Return our modified list
the_pythons
## ['Chapman', 'Idle', 'Gillam', 'Jones', 'Cheese', 'Palin']

4.2 Sequential items

If we want to select more than one sequential item we can use a colon ( : ) between the first index position (inclusive) and the last index position (exclusive).

It is important to remember that the last index is exclusive in this case, it will not be included.

As a reminder our the_pythons list looks like this

_example

If I wanted to select the values Idle, Gillam, Jones the following code:

the_pythons[1:3]
## ['Idle', 'Gillam']

would not give the output we want. Instead I need to provide

the_pythons[1:4]
## ['Idle', 'Gillam', 'Jones']

If I want to select from the beginning or to the end of the list I can leave the position before or after the colon blank respectively.

This first code selects from the start of the list to Gillam - remember the last number is exclusive.

This code selects from Idle at index 1 to the end of the list.

print(the_pythons[:3], the_pythons[1:])
## ['Chapman', 'Idle', 'Gillam'] ['Idle', 'Gillam', 'Jones', 'Cheese', 'Palin']

Methods and attributes

Methods and attributes relate to the objects that we perform them on.

Each object has itâ€™s own methods and attributes that relate to that object.

For example, we can use the method .sort() on our parrots list we created earlier.

  • Firstly we tell python the object we want to work on â€“ here by giving the variable/identifier parrots.
  • Secondly we use the full stop or â€œdot notationâ€
  • Thirdly we call our method â€“ here sort and finish it with round brackets
# A reminder of how we created the original list
parrots = ["Cockatoo" , "Macaw", "Parakeet", "Lorikeet", "Norwegian Blue", "Conure"]

# Use the sort method to sort the list

parrots.sort()

# Print out the parrots list to see what's happened.
parrots
## ['Cockatoo', 'Conure', 'Lorikeet', 'Macaw', 'Norwegian Blue', 'Parakeet']

Here weâ€™re using a method that does not have any mandatory parameters â€“ weâ€™ll look at how you can find out what parameters a method or function has in the next chapter.

As it has no mandatory parameters we complete the method by opening and closing round brackets.

Letâ€™s try using .extend() on the parrots list we created earlier. .extend() adds items to our list.

  • 1st We create a new list, with the objects we want to add.
  • 2nd We tell python the object we want to work on â€“ here by giving the variable/identifier parrots.
  • 3rd We use the full stop or â€œdot notationâ€
  • 4th We call our method â€“ here extend and open our round brackets
  • 5th We need to tell the method what to add - the list we created earlier. We put this in the round brackets.
# Create a new list with more birds

more_parrots = ["Lovebird", "Kea", "Rosella"]

# Use the extend method to add the new list more_parrots to our parrots list

parrots.extend(more_parrots)

# Print out the parrots list to see what's happened.
parrots
## ['Cockatoo', 'Conure', 'Lorikeet', 'Macaw', 'Norwegian Blue', 'Parakeet', 'Lovebird', 'Kea', 'Rosella']

5.2 Importing Pandas

In order to use the functionality of the Pandas package within our Python code; we first need to import it.

We need to import our packages in every script we write.

You should always import the packages youâ€™re going to use at the very ** top ** of your script.

As we mentioned in the last chapter, we have already downloaded the packages we need for this course â€“ they come bundled with the Anaconda Suite.

To use the functions within a package we need to import it by using an import statement:

import pandas as pd

When we import a package we donâ€™t get any feedback itâ€™s worked. In Jupyter the cell will change from a green to blue, and the line number will increase.

  • We start by using the key word import - this is a reserved word in Python, you can see the syntax highlighting in Jupyter, it is bold and green.

  • We then give the package name

  • The keyword as allows us to give a nickname to the package

  • Which here is pd

We donâ€™t have to give nicknames to packages; however, itâ€™s a very common standard; that saves us some typing. Weâ€™ll often need to reference the package containing the function; e.g pd.Series() - which is much faster than pandas.Series().

5.3 Checking Package Versions

All packages have versions; this allows code to be updated, extended or modified as time goes on.

For reproducibility purposes, as well as searching for help it can be important to know which version of a package youâ€™re using.

Most packages follow the PEP8 guidelines we talked about previously and allow you to find the version of a package using the command.

pd.__version__ 

# Note here there's TWO underscores before *and* after version.
## '1.2.4'

Within ONS our current version of Pandas is 0.20.1.

All course material is designed to work with this version of Pandas.

If you have an older version you may find some parts may not work.

If you have a more modern version you may find some small changes; like different parameter names or possibly more streamlined ways to write certain parts of code.

Most versions are backwards compatible so should function as expected.

5.4 Series

Pandas gives us two new object types.

Series are

  • One dimensional arrays
  • Act like columns in a spreadsheet
  • Must have items of the same type (int, float or str)
  • Has a series index â€“ defaults to start at 0

Series have a large number of special methods and procedures associated with them; which weâ€™ll explore in this course.

# I'm manually creating a Series here - we'll talk about why we don't teach this in a second.

python_movies = pd.Series(["And Now For Something Completely Different",
                           "Monty Python and the Holy Grail",
                           "Monty Python's Life of Brian",
                           "Monty Python Live at the Hollywood Bowl",
                           "Monty Python's Meaning of Life",
                           "Monty Python Live (Mostly)"])


# Display the series below the cell.

python_movies

5.5 DataFrames

DataFrames are

  • A two dimensional version of the series object
  • Like a whole spreadsheet
  • Essentially a collection of series objects (one series per column)

where

  • A column can only have one data type
  • Each column can have a different data type
  • The dimensions are labelled similarly to a series object
    • index refers to the row labels â€“ and defaults to starting at 0
    • columns refers to the column labels â€“ or headers.

The DataFrames will have some of the same methods as Series and some different.

film_name live year
And Now For Something Completely Different FALSE 1971
Monty Python and the Holy Grail FALSE 1975
Monty Pythonâ€™s Life of Brian FALSE 1979
Monty Python Live at the Hollywood Bowl FALSE 1982
Monty Pythonâ€™s Meaning of Life FALSE 1983
Monty Python Live (Mostly) TRUE 2014

5.5.1 Why are we not creating series and data frames?

In this course we donâ€™t manually create Series or DataFrame objects within Python.

When we work in Python weâ€™re often reading in data from files; very rarely do we create the data we want from scratch. It can be a useful skill to know â€“ and if you wish to extend your knowledge here is a short tutorial.

The help documentation has a few different sections. As the contents of these are defined by the creator of the function some may have more information in them than others.

This one has:

Signature - the text we use to call the function and the parameters (think options) and arguments (default values) inside of the brackets. Here we have several the parameter n = contols the number of rows returned and parameter called replace = and the default argument for this is False.

Underneath this tells us the Docstring â€“ which is information about the function.

Thirdly parameters gives us more information about the parameters (options) we can set within this function.

Going back to our replace = parameter, we can see that this takes a Boolean argument (True or False) and that it controls if we sample with or without replacement.

At the bottom we have Returns which tells us what the function returns; and underneath this we have Examples - not all functions will have this level of detail in the docstring!

Now we know other parameters we can set for python_movies_df.sample() letâ€™s try returning a sample of 4 rows, and turn replace = to True

python_movies_df.sample(n=4 , replace=True)

Our parameters and their arguments (n=4 and replace=True) go inside of the round brackets of the function. These are seperated by commas.

Jupyter Notebooks also has a rather nice way of accessing the docstring.

Place your cursor somewhere in the object below.

Pressing Shift + Tab once shows the parameters available for the object you are looking at.

Pressing Shift + Tab twice shows the whole docstring

Pressing Shift + Tab a third time makes the tool-tip linger for 10 seconds.

Pressing Shift + Tab a fourth time put the tool-tip into a larger pane in the browser.

.sample() is a fairly simple method â€“ and doesnâ€™t have many parameters and arguments.

Depending on what your function does depends on how many arguments and parameters there may be.
